{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bc5a7c80-b1e8-45f3-8676-ec739ae25dd0","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's a summary:\n\n## 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed the **default test-ID algorithm**. The new IDs don't match v3's, so ADO treats every test as new. Fix by opting back in to the legacy IDs in your csproj:\n\n```xml\n<TestIdGenerationStrategy>Legacy</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n```\n\n## 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a **class-level** context — it no longer carries a specific test name, so accessing `TestName` throws. This is by design since class init runs once, not per-test.\n\n**Fix** — guard or remove the access:\n\n```csharp\n[ClassInitialize]\npublic static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n{\n    // context.TestName is not available here in v4\n    // Move per-test logic to [TestInitialize] instead\n}\n```\n\n## 3. Other key v4 breaking changes to watch for\n\n| Area | Change |\n|---|---|\n| **`[DataRow]` type coercion** | Implicit conversions (e.g., `int` → `long`) no longer happen automatically; types must match exactly. |\n| **`Assert.AreEqual` for collections** | Now does structural/deep comparison — tests relying on reference equality may flip results. |\n| **`TestContext.Properties`** | Removed or read-only in some contexts; code writing to it will break. |\n| **Class/Assembly cleanup timing** | `[ClassCleanup]`/`[AssemblyCleanup]` now run at end-of-class/assembly by default (was end-of-test-run). Shared state assumptions may break. |\n| **Nullable `TestContext`** | The property should now be declared `TestContext?` — the analyzer will warn otherwise. |\n\nWould you like me to apply the fixes to your project files?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0356bb07-90bd-4551-8022-60afad645cc7","outputTokens":487},"id":"1640a843-a459-4f4c-9ab0-931d8812c222","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:25:48.981Z","parentId":"c3d4f6b3-05c8-4e68-9cfd-2faa283c1607"}
